I used the head command to check the data to make sure it looked okay. This does look fine, but most points are under the maximum residue limit. They
do not have to report results under this limit, and often can't detect things under this. Because of that, I'm going to remove the data under this limit, and
instead only factor it in at the end when we are observing the concentrations in different areas. This amount won't be used to detect averages though, as it 
wouldn't make sense to report them as zero when there is certainly a small quantity in the water. The areas without enough will be noted though, and used in 
a way that seems appropriate after analyzing the rest of the data. 

> pfoan <- subset(pfoa, 'Result (ug/L)' != "MRL")
> pfosn <- subset(pfos, 'Result (ug/L)' != "MRL")

This removed all MRL points. I named them the same with n to represent the subsets with reported numbers only.
Unfortunately, in this dataset there is no observance of it's distance to water. This means I have to manually map each from the ocean, set my boundaries for 
each and then create subsets of each county to calculate the averages of each. I put my file into co-pilot and asked it to sort the distances for me as this
would take a very long time to do manually and I cannot use regular data analysis software to do it. I am not copying the full code as that would take up a lot
of space, but this is a sample: 
> close <-c("HINGHAM WATER DEPARTMENT", "HULL WATER DEPARTMENT", "MARBLEHEAD WATER DEPARTMENT", "MARSHFIELD WATER DEPARTMENT",...) 
The parts in each bracket were sorted by copilot. 

> pfoaclose <- pfoa[pfoa$'PWS Name' %in% close, ]
> pfoamed <- pfoa[pfoa$'PWS Name' %in% medium, ]
> pfoafar <- pfoa[pfoa$'PWS Name' %in% far, ]
> pfosclose <- pfos[pfos$'PWS Name' %in% close, ]
> pfosmed <- pfos[pfos$'PWS Name' %in% medium, ]
> pfosfar <- pfos[pfos$'PWS Name' %in% far, ]

I separated the initial subsets as I do want to keep track of the amount of data with MRL. If one subset has siginificantly more than another, it could still
have a higher mean and median as the points could be skewed. 

